## DSL & IR Deep Dive

### The DSL Philosophy

DSL = **Domain Specific Language**. It lets authors write episodes naturally:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Natural, readable
const wa = new {{ pascalCase name }}TrackBuilder(b);
wa.at(1000).receive({ from: "John", text: "Hello!" });
wa.at(2000).typingStart({ from: "John" });
wa.at(3000).send({ text: "Hi there!" });

// ❌ BAD: Too low-level
b.track("app").point(1000, {
kind: "APP", appId: "app_{{ snakeCase name }}", type: "MESSAGE_RECEIVED",
payload: { from: "John", text: "Hello!", conversationId: "conv_1" }
});
```

### IR: The Contract

IR (Intermediate Representation) is the **contract** between DSL and engine.

```typescript
// ir/payloads.ts
export interface {{ pascalCase name }}Payloads {
MESSAGE_RECEIVED: { from: string; text: string; conversationId: string };
MESSAGE_SENT: { text: string; conversationId: string };
TYPING_START: { conversationId: string; actor: string };
TYPING_END: { conversationId: string; actor: string };
}
```

**Why type payloads?**
1. Compile-time checking
2. IDE autocomplete
3. Self-documenting
4. Discriminated unions for exhaustive switches

